  "stage": {
    "id": "course_2_architecture",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "YOLO Architecture Deep Dive",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "single_stage_detector",
        "title": "Single-Stage Detection: YOLO's Core Insight",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- end-to-end prediction\n- no region proposals\n- speed advantage\n\nThe genius of YOLO: skip the region proposal step entirely. Two-stage detectors first find candidate regions (RPN), then refine them. YOLO predicts directly from the entire image.\n\nThis saves computation dramatically — hence \"real-time.\" You sacrifice some accuracy (YOLO can miss overlapping objects), but gain speed. It's a fundamental speed-accuracy tradeoff that made real-world deployment practical.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "darknet53",
        "title": "Darknet-53: The Feature Extraction Backbone",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- 53 convolutional layers\n- hierarchical features\n- efficient design\n\nDarknet-53 has 53 convolutional layers — hence the name. It's the \"backbone\" that transforms raw images into rich feature representations. Earlier layers detect low-level features (edges), middle layers detect shapes, and deeper layers detect high-level patterns.\n\nYOLOv3 chose 53 layers as a sweet spot: deep enough to learn complex patterns, but efficient enough to run in real-time. Compare to ResNet-152 (152 layers), which is slower but slightly more accurate.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "residual_connections",
        "title": "Residual Connections: Training Deep Networks",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- skip connections\n- identity mapping\n- gradient flow\n\nWithout skip connections, gradients can vanish when backpropagating through 50+ layers. Skip connections create \"shortcuts\" where the gradient can flow directly, plus a residual term: y = F(x) + x instead of just y = F(x).\n\nThink of it like adding a \"fast lane\" to a deep highway — information (and gradients) can take shortcuts, while the main path learns additional transformations. This is why Darknet-53 can be so deep without vanishing gradients.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "batch_normalization",
        "title": "Batch Normalization: Stabilizing Training",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- feature normalization\n- internal covariate shift\n- higher learning rates\n\nDuring training, each layer receives inputs from previous layers, whose distributions constantly shift (internal covariate shift). Batch normalization fixes layer inputs to mean=0, variance=1, then lets the network learn its own scale/shift via learnable parameters.\n\nBenefit: the network sees more stable input distributions, allowing faster learning and higher learning rates. In Darknet-53, batch norm follows every conv layer except the final output layer.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "leaky_relu",
        "title": "Leaky ReLU: Better Gradient Flow",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- activation function\n- negative slope\n- dead neuron prevention\n\nStandard ReLU outputs 0 for all negative inputs. During training, if a neuron always outputs 0, it receives zero gradients and never learns (\"dead neuron\").\n\nLeaky ReLU (with slope 0.01 or 0.1) ensures gradients flow even for negative inputs. This keeps all neurons \"alive\" and learning. Across 53 layers, this small change significantly improves training stability and convergence speed.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "fpn",
        "title": "Feature Pyramid Network: Multi-Scale Features",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- hierarchical features\n- coarse-to-fine\n- small object detection\n\nDarknet-53 progressively reduces spatial dimensions (via stride-2 convolutions), creating a hierarchy: high-resolution early features, low-resolution deep features. FPN combines these by upsampling coarse features and fusing them with fine features.\n\nResult: feature maps at different scales, each encoding different details. This is why YOLOv3 predicts at 3 scales (13×13, 26×26, 52×52) — it leverages this pyramid structure to detect small, medium, and large objects.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "Feature Pyramid Networks extract multi-scale features by: What's the approach?",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "Running the backbone once and using different layer outputs",
        "Running the backbone multiple times at different image resolutions",
        "Applying nearest-neighbor upsampling to coarser features"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Running the backbone once and using different layer outputs",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
    },
